:"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Melville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the various places in Normandy called Malleville, from Latin <i>mala</i> ‘bad’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’.","Irish (mainly Ulster): English surname adopted by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilmhichíl</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maoilmhichil</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘devotee of (Saint) Michael’.","History: The American novelist Herman Melville (1819–91) was a descendantof the Scottish Melvilles. His maternal grandfather was the revolutionary war general Peter Gansevoort (born 1749 in Albany, NY). His paternal grandfather was Maj. Thomas Melville of Boston. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from Maol Mhichíl, a chief of Síol Muireadhaigh (County Roscommon) in the 9th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Melvin","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Melville   with alternation of final <i>-l</i> and <i>-n</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhín</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of Maoilmhín’, a personal name meaning ‘gentle chieftain’."]},{"name":"Mulville","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Melville  ."]},{"name":"Mellin","meanings":["Scottish (Glamorgan): variant of   Melville  .","German: habitational name from any of various places so called.","English: variant of   Melling  ."]},{"name":"Mulvihill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Paddy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhichíl</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) Michael’. The Anglicized form was sometimes abbreviated into   Melville  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Laird Thomas Walter De Melville Of Fife was born in 1360, in Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland, his father, John Melville Of Fife, was 26 and his mother, Isobel Cumin, was 39. He married Margaret Ayr in 1381. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1429, in Raith House, Fife, Scotland, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1360–1429":"1360–1429","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1382–1468":"1382–1468","1400–1478":"1400–1478","1335–1379":"1335–13